{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501743"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:33:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1785"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1785"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0.14,0.65,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1785"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77149"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with collapse after standing up. He reports three days of fatigue, myalgia, and poor appetite. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He usually surfs several times per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 60/40 mmHg supine, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. He has generalised hyperpigmentation, particularly noticeable in sun-exposed areas. His chest is clear and abdomen is soft and non-tender. Despite receiving 2L of intravenous crystalloid, his blood pressure remains 65/45 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 128 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 6.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 12.0 mmol/L (3.0-8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 140 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral resonium","Oral sodium bicarbonate","Hypertonic saline infusion","Intravenous hydrocortisone","Adrenaline infusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of acute adrenal crisis (Addisonian crisis): hypotension resistant to fluid resuscitation, hyponatraemia, hyperkalaemia, and hyperpigmentation. The crisis has likely been precipitated by an intercurrent viral illness, as suggested by his myalgia and mild fever. The presence of hyperpigmentation suggests chronic primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison\u0027s disease) that has likely gone undiagnosed until this acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive emergency treatment, typically given as 100mg immediately followed by continuous infusion or 6-hourly doses. This replaces the missing cortisol and helps restore vascular tone, cardiac contractility, and blood pressure. It also helps correct the metabolic derangements through its mineralocorticoid effects. The diagnosis can be confirmed later with cortisol and ACTH levels, but treatment should not be delayed while awaiting results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral resonium\u003C/strong\u003E would treat the hyperkalaemia but not address the underlying cause. While the potassium of 6.2 mmol/L is concerning, treating the primary condition with glucocorticoids will help correct the electrolyte disturbance through improved sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion. The hyperkalaemia in adrenal crisis is primarily due to mineralocorticoid deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the underlying pathology. While metabolic acidosis may be present in adrenal crisis due to decreased gluconeogenesis and poor tissue perfusion, administering bicarbonate without correcting the cortisol deficiency is inappropriate and may worsen intracellular acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertonic saline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the hyponatraemia in adrenal crisis is primarily due to mineralocorticoid deficiency rather than free water excess. The sodium deficit is accompanied by volume depletion, and isotonic saline along with glucocorticoid replacement is the appropriate fluid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenaline infusion\u003C/strong\u003E might temporarily improve blood pressure but would not address the underlying cortisol deficiency. Vasopressors are rarely needed if appropriate doses of hydrocortisone and fluids are given. The hypotension in adrenal crisis responds dramatically to glucocorticoid replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the initial resuscitation with hydrocortisone and fluids, the patient will require investigation for the underlying cause of their adrenal insufficiency, education about the condition, and long-term replacement with oral glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute adrenocortical insufficiency requires immediate treatment with intravenous hydrocortisone and fluid resuscitation.","The triad of hypotension, hyponatraemia, and hyperkalaemia is characteristic of adrenal crisis.","Intercurrent illness is a common precipitant of adrenal crisis in patients with underlying adrenal insufficiency.","Hyperpigmentation in sun-exposed areas is a classic sign of chronic primary adrenal insufficiency."],"references":["Konick-McMahan J. Crisis management: Acute adrenal insufficiency. Nursing2020 Critical Care. 2006 Sep 1;1(5):52-7.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77149"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1785"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77149"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T22:17:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T22:19:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1785"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93969"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji